 Internal Buffer of Readable Stream
In Node.js, when data flows through a readable stream, it is temporarily stored in memory before being consumed. This temporary storage is known as the internal buffer.

📦 What Is It?
The internal buffer contains the chunks of data that the stream has received but not yet consumed.
It changes dynamically as new chunks arrive or are read.
Its size is controlled by the highWaterMark option passed while creating the stream.

🛠️ Example: Reading Internal Buffer
stream.on("readable", () => {    console.log(stream.readableLength);  // Shows bytes available in buffer    
console.log(stream.read());          // Reads chunk from buffer    
console.log(stream.readableLength);  // Shows remaining bytes
});

📝 Breakdown:
readableLength: Number of bytes currently in the internal buffer.
read(): Consumes data from the buffer.
After each read(), the internal buffer size decreases.

💡 Key Points:
The 'readable' event is emitted when a chunk is available to read.
The buffer doesn't grow infinitely—it is capped by highWaterMark.
This method gives manual control over reading, unlike 'data' event which auto-consumes.